📊 Data Preprocessing Guide: Outliers & Feature Scaling

This repository contains a complete MATLAB workflow for cleaning and preparing datasets before training Machine Learning models. 

## 🔍 1. Outlier Detection & Handling (IQR Method)

### What is an Outlier?
An outlier is a data point that is significantly different from the remaining data. Outliers can skew statistical models and corrupt predictions.

### The Interquartile Range (IQR) Formula
To find outliers mathematically, we use percentiles:
* **Q1 (25th Percentile):** The middle value of the lower half of the data.
* **Q3 (75th Percentile):** The middle value of the upper half of the data.
* **IQR:** The distance between Q3 and Q1 ($IQR = Q3 - Q1$).

We build logical bounds (fences). Any value outside these fences is flagged as an outlier:
* **Lower Bound:** $Q1 - 1.5 \times IQR$
* **Upper Bound:** $Q3 + 1.5 \times IQR$

### Handling Methods
1. **Removal:** Deleting the entire row containing the outlier.
2. **Winsorization (Capping):** Replacing extreme values with the closest legal bound limit.

---

## 📈 2. Feature Scaling

### Why do we scale features?
When variables have completely different ranges (e.g., Age: 0–80 vs. Salary: 0–150,000), distance-based models can ignore the smaller feature. Scaling solves this problem.

### Min-Max Normalization
Rescales the data so that every single value fits precisely between **0 and 1**.
$$\text{Normalized Value} = \frac{x - \text{min}(x)}{\text{max}(x) - \text{min}(x)}$$

### Z-Score Standardization
Transforms the data so that the **Mean becomes 0** and the **Standard Deviation becomes 1**.
$$\text{Standardized Value} = \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}$$

clc; clear; clearvars; % Clear the command window and workspace memory

%% ========================================================================
%% PART 1: OUTLIER DETECTION (IQR METHOD)
%% ========================================================================

filename = 'HousingData.csv';             % Define the dataset file name
data = readtable(filename);               % Read the CSV file into a table
disp("--- First 5 Rows of Housing Data ---");
disp(head(data, 5));                      % Display the first 5 rows of the table

vars = {'RM', 'MEDV'};                    % Specify columns to check for outliers

for i = 1:length(vars)                    % Loop through each specified variable
    col = data.(vars{i});                 % Extract the current column data
    Q1 = quantile(col, 0.25);             % Calculate the 1st quartile (25th percentile)
    Q3 = quantile(col, 0.75);             % Calculate the 3rd quartile (75th percentile)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1;                        % Calculate the Interquartile Range

    lowerBound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR;          % Determine the lower limit for normal values
    upperBound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR;          % Determine the upper limit for normal values

    % Find logical index where values exceed the limits
    outliers = (col < lowerBound) | (col > upperBound); 
    
    % Print how many outliers were found in the current variable
    fprintf("%s variable has %d outliers.\n", vars{i}, sum(outliers));
    
    % Save a true/false outlier mask column inside the original table
    data.([vars{i} '_Outlier']) = outliers; 
end                                       % End of the detection loop


%% ========================================================================
%% PART 2: HANDLING OUTLIERS
%% ========================================================================

% --- Method 1: Removing Outliers Entirely ---
% Remove rows where 'RM' or 'MEDV' are marked as true outliers
data_removed = data(~data.RM_Outlier & ~data.MEDV_Outlier, :); 

% Print the number of remaining rows after removal
fprintf("\n[Method 1] Outliers removed: %d rows remaining.\n", height(data_removed));


% --- Method 2: Capping Outliers (Winsorization) ---
data_winsor = data;                       % Create a clean copy of the original data

for i = 1:length(vars)                    % Loop through each variable again
    col = data.(vars{i});                 % Get the column data
    Q1 = quantile(col, 0.25);             % Get 25th percentile
    Q3 = quantile(col, 0.75);             % Get 75th percentile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1;                        % Get Interquartile Range
    
    lowerBound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR;          % Calculate lower bound
    upperBound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR;          % Calculate upper bound
    
    col(col < lowerBound) = lowerBound;   % Replace values below lower bound with the boundary
    col(col > upperBound) = upperBound;   % Replace values above upper bound with the boundary
    
    data_winsor.(vars{i}) = col;          % Save the capped column back to winsorized table
end                                       % End of the capping loop

disp("[Method 2] Winsorization applied successfully!");


%% ========================================================================
%% PART 3: FEATURE SCALING
%% ========================================================================

% --- Step 1: Load Scaling Data (Titanic Train Dataset) ---
data_scaling = readtable('train.csv');    % Load the training dataset
disp(" ");
disp("--- First 5 Rows of Scaling Data (train.csv) ---");
disp(head(data_scaling, 5));              % Show the first 5 rows

numericVars = {'Age', 'Fare'};            % Choose numeric columns to scale


% --- Method 1: Min-Max Normalization (0 to 1) ---
fprintf("\n--- Min-Max Normalization Results ---\n");
for i = 1:length(numericVars)             % Loop through columns to scale
    col = data_scaling.(numericVars{i});  % Select current column
    colMin = min(col, [], 'omitnan');     % Find minimum value, ignoring missing values (NaN)
    colMax = max(col, [], 'omitnan');     % Find maximum value, ignoring missing values (NaN)
    
    % Apply Min-Max formula: (x - min) / (max - min)
    data_scaling.([numericVars{i} '_MinMax']) = (col - colMin) ./ (colMax - colMin);
    
    % Print the old range and the new scaled transformation message
    fprintf('%s -> Scaled from range [%.2f, %.2f] to [0, 1].\n', numericVars{i}, colMin, colMax);
end                                       % End of Min-Max loop


% --- Method 2: Z-Score Standardization ---
fprintf("\n--- Z-Score Standardization Results ---\n");
for i = 1:length(numericVars)             % Loop through the numeric features
    col = data_scaling.(numericVars{i});  % Select the column data
    mu = mean(col, 'omitnan');            % Calculate the average (mean) of the column
    sigma = std(col, 'omitnan');          % Calculate the standard deviation of the column
    
    % Apply Z-Score formula: (x - mean) / std
    data_scaling.([numericVars{i} '_Zscore']) = (col - mu) ./ sigma;
    
    % Print the calculated mean and standard deviation values for verification
    fprintf('%s -> Mean: %.2f, Std: %.2f\n', numericVars{i}, mu, sigma);
end                                       % End of Z-Score loop

