# Hyperparameter Tuning and Overfitting Prevention in Decision Trees

## Abstract
This section demonstrates how hyperparameter adjustment—specifically controlling minimum leaf size—mitigates overfitting in Decision Tree Regression models using MATLAB's `fitrtree` function. While highly complex trees tend to memorize training data, simpler and properly pruned models generalize significantly better when evaluated on unseen test data.

---

## Technical Overview
- **Default Tree Model (`mdl_tree_default`):** Fits an unconstrained decision tree. It grows deeply to capture subtle dataset fluctuations, which often leads to **overfitting** (high variance).
- **Tuned Tree Model (`mdl_tree_tuned`):** Constrains tree depth by setting `'MinLeafSize', 50`. Requiring at least 50 samples per terminal leaf forces the algorithm to create broader generalizations, reducing complexity and improving performance on unseen data.

---

## MATLAB Implementation

```matlab
% Load concrete compressive strength dataset into workspace
load("concreteData.mat");

% Define predictor variables (features) as a formula string
predictors = 'Cement+BlastFurnaceSlag+FlyAsh+Water+Superplasticizer+CoarseAggregate+FineAggregate+Age';

% Train default regression tree (unconstrained depth)
mdl_tree_default = fitrtree(concreteData, ['CompressiveStrength ~ ', predictors]);

% Display heading for default tree rules
fprintf("\n\nDefault Tree Model:\n");

% Display decision rules for default tree in command window
view(mdl_tree_default);

% Train tuned regression tree (constrained using minimum leaf size)
mdl_tree_tuned = fitrtree(concreteData, ['CompressiveStrength ~ ', predictors], 'MinLeafSize', 50);

% Display heading for tuned tree rules
fprintf("\n\nTuned Tree Model:\n");

% Display decision rules for tuned tree in command window
view(mdl_tree_tuned);

